EmoTech Solutions, a prominent technology firm focusing in emotion-driven solutions, has recently hired me. EmoTech Solutions is a pioneer in the development of cutting-edge technologies that use artificial intelligence and machine learning to comprehend and interpret human emotions. I have been entrusted with an important project to increase EmoTech Solutions' products and transform the way emotions are interpreted and evaluated as a specialist in speech emotion recognition.

The emphasis is on building advanced speech emotion recognition algorithms and systems capable of reliably detecting and analyzing emotions in spoken language. The purpose is to deliver useful insights and actionable data to industries such as customer service, market research, healthcare, entertainment, and others. EmoTech Solutions' goal is to empower enterprises to better customer experiences, personalize services, and increase overall emotional well-being by accurately collecting and comprehending human emotions.

Loading the dataset¶

In this section, I have loaded the 3 datasets.¶

The datasets are basically audio files, therefore we will make a dataset, that contains the file paths and the respective labels (fear, angry, disgust, neutral, sad, ps, happy).

Since different datasets have different filenames, extracting the labels for each dataset has to be done differntly. I already know what the filenames look like, therefore I have done it directly.

Links to the Datasets

  1. TESS: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/ejlok1/toronto-emotional-speech-set-tess
  2. RAVDESS: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/uwrfkaggler/ravdess-emotional-speech-audio
  3. CREMA-D: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/ejlok1/cremad

The links above clearly explain the file naming convention and the labels and paths can be further extracted like this:

1. TESS_paths and TESS_labels are empty lists that will be filled with the TESS dataset's file directories and labels, respectively.¶
2. The os.walk() method is used to navigate the directory structure indicated in the path ('/Users/ayushphukan/Downloads/Jupyter Projects/TESS Toronto emotional speech set data'). It loops over all of the directories, subdirectories, and files contained inside the provided root directory.¶
3. The loop iterates over the file_names list, which holds the names of all the files in the current directory, throughout each iteration of os.walk().¶
4. The code appends the whole file path to the TESS_paths list for each file using os.path.join(root_dir, file_name).¶
5. The label is extracted from each file name by the code. It splits the file name on the "" character and returns the final member of the list (file_name.split("")[-1]). The label is then divided again on the "." character, and the first member of the resultant list is taken (label_name.split(."")[0]).¶
6. The retrieved label is changed to lowercase and inserted to the TESS_labels list using the lower() function.¶
7 . When the loop is ended, the code outputs "Dataset loaded" to signify that the loading procedure is complete.¶
In [2]:
TESS_paths = []
TESS_labels = []

for root_dir, _, file_names in os.walk('/Users/ayushphukan/Downloads/Jupyter Projects/TESS Toronto emotional speech set data'):
    for file_name in file_names:
        TESS_paths.append(os.path.join(root_dir, file_name))
        print(file_name)
        label_name = file_name.split("_")[-1]
        label_name = label_name.split(".")[0]
        TESS_labels.append(label_name.lower())

print("Dataset loaded")

All Paths and Labels are now loaded¶

Now we need to change the label names to same in all datasets so that we can then merge the 3 datasets together¶

Therefore, here I have created a function to finf the unique labels present in the dataset

  1. unique_list is an empty list that will be populated with unique labels.

  2. The code uses a for loop to iterate over each element x in the labels list.

  3. Within the loop, the code checks if the current element x is already present in the unique_list using the condition if x not in unique_list.

  4. If the element x is not found in the unique_list, it means it is a unique label, and the code appends it to the unique_list using unique_list.append(x).

The second loop simply prints these unique labels.

In [11]:
def lst_unique_finder(labels):
    unique_list=[]
    for x in labels:
        if x not in unique_list:
            unique_list.append(x)
        
    for x in unique_list:
        print(x)
In [12]:
lst_unique_finder(CREMAD_labels)

ang
neu
dis
sad
fea
hap

So, we can change the names respectively using a while loop.¶

  1. I've set i=0 initially and a while loop is run till i < the length of the CREMAD_labels list

  2. i is being used to basically access the values using the index.

  3. Then, the respective changes are made.

In [13]:
i=0

while i < len(CREMAD_labels):

    if CREMAD_labels[i]=='ang':
        CREMAD_labels[i]=CREMAD_labels[i].replace("ang", "angry")
        
    elif CREMAD_labels[i]=='neu':

Working with sound¶

  1. To digitize a sound wave, we must convert the signal into a series of numbers that can be fed into our models. This is accomplished by measuring the amplitude of the sound at regular periods of time. Each of these measurements is referred to as a sample, and the sample rate is the number of samples taken each second and this can be visualised using a spectrum

  1. The Spectrum is the set of frequencies that are combined together to produce a signal. The Spectrum plots all of the frequencies that are present in the signal along with the strength or amplitude of each frequency.

  1. But there's a problem with spectrums too. Spectrums only help visualise one instance in the entire audio file and the audio/sound changes with time and different frequencies have changes in amplitude over time. To visualise the change over time, Spectrograms are used.

A Spectrogram of a signal is a 'picture' of the signal that traces its Spectrum with time. Time is plotted on the x-axis, while frequency is plotted on the y-axis. It's as if we took the Spectrum at various points of time and then merged them all together into a single plot.¶

It employs several colors to represent the amplitude or intensity of each frequency. The higher the energy of the signal, the brighter the hue. Each vertical'slice' of the Spectrogram is effectively the Spectrum of the signal at that point in time, displaying how the signal intensity is divided across all frequencies present in the signal at that point.¶

  1. The waveform is plotted using the librosa.display.waveshow() method, which depicts the amplitude of the audio stream with time.

  1. The librosa.stft() function computes the Short-Time Fourier Transform (STFT), a time-frequency representation of an audio stream.

  1. The librosa.amplitude_to_db() function transforms the amplitude values of the STFT to decibels, resulting in a more perceptually relevant spectrogram representation.

  1. The spectrogram, which visualizes the strength of distinct frequency components over time, is plotted using the librosa.display.specshow() method.

Overall, librosa allows us to extract and display significant properties of audio signals, which aids in the analysis and comprehension of audio data.

Also, we have used matplotlib for visualising the audio file and spectrogram.¶

I have plotted each of the emotions once

In [33]:
def display_wave(data, sampling_rate, title):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))
    plt.title(title)
    librosa.display.waveshow(data, sr=sampling_rate)
    plt.show()

def display_spectrogram(data, sampling_rate, title):
    transform_stft = librosa.stft(data)
    
    
    amplitude_db = librosa.amplitude_to_db(abs(transform_stft))
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))
    plt.title(title)
    librosa.display.specshow(amplitude_db, sr=sampling_rate, x_axis='time', y_axis='hz')
    plt.colorbar()

Data Augmentation¶

Here, we could have done Data Augmentation, a technique that is commonly used in machine learning and audio processing to improve the diversity and unpredictability of training data. The enhanced data provides fluctuations in speed or length by using transformations such as time-stretching, which can assist improve the generalization and resilience of the models trained on the data. Data augmentation contributes to the creation of a more complete and representative dataset, avoiding overfitting and improving the model's capacity to handle diverse variances in real-world circumstances. Due to hardware issues, this process would take too long to run, but I will still explain what could have been done.

In our case I could have stretched the audio files to improve the diversity of the training data:

  1. The augment_data function accepts two parameters: y (audio waveform) and sr (sampling rate).

  2. The data augmentation technique utilized in this code piece is time-stretching.

  3. Time-stretching is a method of increasing the speed of an audio source without changing its pitch. It may be used to accelerate or decelerate the audio.

  4. The librosa.effects.time_stretch function is used to time-stretch the audio waveform y input. The rate parameter defines the stretching factor, with a value less than one slowing down and a value larger than one speeding up the audio. The rate is set to 0.8 in this example, which slows down the audio by 20%.

The function then returns the time-stretched audio waveform y_stretch.

In [41]:
def augment_data(y, sr):
    # Time-stretching
    y_stretch = librosa.effects.time_stretch(y, rate=0.8)  # rate > 1 speeds up, rate < 1 slows down

    return y_stretch

Mel-frequency Cepstral Coefficients (MFCCs) are extracted from an audio file using the extract_mfcc function. Let's dissect the code and figure out what it does:¶

What we are doing here is using mel spectrograms(their cepstral coeffiecients). Why they are better than normal spectrograms is because humans do not perceive frequencies in a linear fashion. We are more sensitive to differences in lower frequencies than changes in higher frequencies. Therefore a better scale to visualise the spectrogram is a mel scale.

It is a scale of pitches, such that each unit is judged by listeners to be equal in pitch distance from the next.

1. The method extract_mfcc accepts an audio_path parameter, which specifies the path to an audio file.¶
2. The audio file is loaded using librosa.load with the sr=None option in this code snippet, which loads the audio file without resampling and returns the waveform y and sampling rate sr.¶
3. The augment_data function or other strategies for introducing changes in the data can be used to the audio waveform, which was commented out in this code.¶
4. librosa.feature.mfcc is then used to extract the MFCC features from the original audio waveform. The n_mfcc=40 option states that we want to extract 40 MFCC coefficients.¶
5. The code checks the length of the extracted MFCC features. If the length is less than max_pad_len (400 in this case), the code pads the features with zeros to match the maximum length using np.pad. If the length exceeds max_pad_len, the code truncates the features to max_pad_len.¶
6. Finally, the function returns the extracted MFCC features as a numpy array mfcc.¶

Overall, this code extracts MFCC features from an audio file and ensures that the extracted features have a consistent length (max_pad_len) by either padding or truncating. The MFCC features can be used as input to machine learning models for audio classification or other audio-related tasks.

In [42]:
max_pad_len = 400
def extract_mfcc(audio_path):
    y, sr = librosa.load(audio_path, sr=None, mono=True)
    
    # Apply data augmentation
    #y_stretch= augment_data(y, sr)
    
    # Extract MFCCs for original, time-stretched and noise-added signals
    mfcc = librosa.feature.mfcc(y=y, sr=sr, n_mfcc=40)
    #mfcc_stretch = librosa.feature.mfcc(y=y_stretch, sr=sr, n_mfcc=40)
    
    # If maximum length exceeds mfcc lengths then pad the remaining ones
    if (max_pad_len > mfcc.shape[1]):
        pad_width = max_pad_len - mfcc.shape[1]
        mfcc = np.pad(mfcc, pad_width=((0, 0), (0, pad_width)), mode='constant')

    # Else cutoff the remaining parts
    else:
        mfcc = mfcc[:, :max_pad_len]

    # Match the length of the time-stretched MFCC features with the original ones
#     if (mfcc.shape[1] > mfcc_stretch.shape[1]):
#         pad_width = mfcc.shape[1] - mfcc_stretch.shape[1]
#         mfcc_stretch = np.pad(mfcc_stretch, pad_width=((0, 0), (0, pad_width)), mode='constant')
#     else:
#          mfcc_stretch = mfcc_stretch[:, :mfcc.shape[1]]

    
    # Combine the MFCC features into a single array
    #mfcc_combined = np.concatenate((mfcc, mfcc_stretch), axis=0)
    
    return mfcc
    #return mfcc_combined

Applying the extract_mfcc function to each element in the 'Speech' column of the DataFrame df. It extracts the MFCC features from audio files specified by the file paths in the 'Speech' column and stores the resulting MFCC features in the X_mfcc variable.¶

In [43]:

The shape (15538,) indicates that the variable X_mfcc has a one-dimensional array with a length of 15,538. This suggests that the MFCC features have been extracted from 15,538 audio files, and each audio file is represented by a one-dimensional array of MFCC coefficients.¶

In [44]:
X_mfcc.shape
Out[44]:
(15538,)

X = [x for x in X_mfcc] loops over the X_mfcc array, transforming each element to a Python list and saving it in the variable X. X = np.array(X) then transforms the list X to a numpy array.¶

The resultant X array has the dimensions (15538, 40, 400). This indicates that the dataset has 15,538 samples. Each sample is a two-dimensional array of MFCC coefficients that represents a single audio file. The first size 40 dimension reflects the number of MFCC coefficients extracted per audio file, while the second size 400 dimension represents the maximum length of the MFCC features after padding or truncation.

In summary, the code converts the extracted MFCC features (X_mfcc) from a list format to a numpy array (X) and reshapes it into a three-dimensional array, where the first dimension represents the number of samples, the second dimension the number of MFCC coefficients, and the third dimension the length of each MFCC feature.¶

Converting the list of MFCC features to a numpy array enhances the efficiency and versatility of data handling, preparing the data for subsequent analysis and modeling tasks.

In [45]:
X= [x for x in X_mfcc]
X=np.array(X)
X.shape
Out[45]:
(15538, 40, 400)

[StandardScaler().fit_transform(x.reshape(40, 400)) for x in X] carries out two procedures on the MFCC feature X:¶

  1. X's MFCC features are reshaped from a two-dimensional array of form (40, 400) to the original shape (40, 400). The reshape approach is used, with 40 representing the number of MFCC coefficients and 400 representing the length of each MFCC feature. This is necessary because machine learning models typically expect input data to have consistent dimensions

  2. Standardization: The reshaped MFCC features are then standardized using scikit-learn's StandardScaler. Standardization is the process of altering data to have a zero mean and unit variance. This is accomplished by removing the mean of each characteristic and dividing by its standard deviation. It Ensures that each feature has a consistent scale and distribution. This prevents certain characteristics from dominating the learning process and guarantees that the model can learn equally from all features.

In [46]:
X = np.array([StandardScaler().fit_transform(x.reshape(40, 400)) for x in X])

Here, we are adding an extra dimension to the end of the array X to increase its dimensions. This is accomplished through the usage of the np.expand_dims() method.¶

By setting axis=-1, the additional dimension is inserted as the array's last dimension. As a result, the form of X will change to (15538, 40, 400, 1).

Why we are doing this¶

Since, we are going us neural networks, specifically CNN, it requires input data to have a 4-dimensional shape (batch_size, height, width, channels), where channels refers to the number of input channels.

Creating the LSTM model¶

In [52]:
import tensorflow as tf
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold
from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold
from keras.models import Sequential
from keras.layers import Dense, Dropout, Flatten, Conv2D, MaxPooling2D, LSTM, TimeDistributed
from keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping

Now we will work on the LSTM model, which is a type of recurrent neural network (RNN) that is well-suited for sequential data such as speech signals. We have chosen to use the LSTM model because of its ability to capture long-term dependencies in the input sequence.¶

In order to evaluate the performance of our LSTM model, we will be using k-fold cross-validation. This allows us to assess the model's performance on multiple subsets of the data and obtain more robust performance metrics.

In this case as we have used "num_folds"=5, what kfold basically does is, it divides the dataset into 5 parts, and runs the model 5 times with each part being the test/ validation set once.

1. acc_per_fold = [] and loss_per_fold = []: These lists will be used to store the accuracy and loss numbers for each fold during cross-validation. This will allow us to track the model's performance on each fold.¶
2. Inputs = X, and targets = Y: Here, we combine the input features (X) and the associated target labels (y). This guarantees that the input and output data are appropriately aligned during the cross-validation procedure.¶
3. kfold = KFold(n_splits=num_folds, shuffle=True): We define the K-fold cross-validator object with the required number of folds (num_folds) and enable data shuffling with shuffle=True. This randomizes the order of the samples to avoid bias caused by data ordering.¶
4. fold_no = 1: This variable keeps track of the current fold number during the cross-validation procedure.¶
In [53]:
num_folds = 5

# Define per-fold score containers
acc_per_fold = []
loss_per_fold = []

# Merge inputs and targets
inputs = X
targets = y

# Define the K-fold Cross Validator
kfold = KFold(n_splits=num_folds, shuffle=True)

# K-fold Cross Validation model evaluation
fold_no = 1
history_per_fold = []

Now, let's configure the optimizer for our LSTM model. We have chosen to use the Adam optimizer, which is an extension of the stochastic gradient descent (SGD) algorithm. Adam is well-suited for deep learning tasks and offers efficient optimization of model parameters.¶

optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.legacy.Adam(learning_rate=0.01): Here, We create an instance of the Adam optimizer with a learning rate of 0.01. The learning rate determines the step size at each iteration of the optimization process, influencing how quickly the model adapts to the training data.

In [54]:
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam
optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.legacy.Adam(learning_rate=0.01)

Now, we can start with the training process of our LSTM model within each fold of the cross-validation. We will iterate over the folds using the kfold.split() method and train the model for each fold.¶

1. Train and test in kfold.split(inputs, targets): This loop iterates over the train and test indices produced from the kfold for each fold.split() is a method. Within each fold, we can train the model on one part of the data (train) and evaluate its performance on another subset (test).¶
2. The variables num_rows, num_columns, num_channels, and num_labels determine the dimensions and number of classes for our input data and target labels.¶
3. Model Architecture: Using the Keras Sequential API, we define an LSTM model architecture. The model is made up of numerous layers:¶

a. Convolutional Layers: We add two Conv2D layers, each with 64 and 128 filters, followed by ReLU activation functions. These layers extract useful information from the input data.


b. MaxPooling Layers: To minimize the spatial dimensions of the feature maps, we use MaxPooling2D layers with a pool size of (2, 2).


c. Dropout Layers: To minimize overfitting during training, we propose Dropout layers with a dropout rate of 0.2.


d. TimeDistributed Layer: To flatten the output of the Conv2D layers, we add a TimeDistributed layer with the Flatten operation.


e. LSTM Layer: To generate a single output for sequence classification, we include an LSTM layer with 64 units and set return_sequences=False.


f. Dropout Layer: We apply another Dropout layer with a dropout rate of 0.5 to further regularize the LSTM layer.


g. Dense Layer: Finally, we add a Dense layer with num_labels units and a softmax activation function to produce the output probabilities for each class.

4. model.compile(): We compile the model by specifying the loss function (categorical_crossentropy for multi-class classification), the optimizer (which we previously created), and the evaluation measure (accuracy).¶
5. model.summary(): This statement displays a summary of the model's architecture, including the layers, output shapes, and number of trainable parameters.¶
In [55]:
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Conv2D, MaxPooling2D, LSTM, Dense, Dropout, Flatten

for train, test in kfold.split(inputs, targets):
    num_rows = 40
    num_columns = 400
    num_channels = 1
    num_labels = 7

    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', input_shape=(num_rows, num_columns, num_channels)))
    model.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.25))

    model.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
    model.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.25))

    model.add(Flatten())
    model.add(Dense(256, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(0.5))

    model.add(Dense(num_labels, activation='softmax'))

model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
model.summary()

This is a Keras callback function that allows us to halt the training process early based on certain criteria. In this situation, we select 'val_loss' as the monitor, which means that the validation loss will be monitored throughout training.¶

monitor='val_loss': To determine when to cease training, we want to monitor the validation loss. The validation loss, as opposed to the training loss, is a measure of how well the model performs on the validation set.

patience=5: The patience parameter specifies how many epochs to wait before terminating training if the observed quantity (in this case, validation loss) does not improve. Training will be terminated early if the validation loss does not improve for 5 consecutive epochs.

In [56]:
early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=5)

We use the fit function to train the model on the training data. Here are the parameters used:¶

  1. inputs[train] and targets[train]: These are the input features and target labels for the current fold of training data.

  1. batch_size=512: The number of samples to use in each training batch.

  1. epochs=100: The number of times to iterate over the entire training dataset.

  1. validation_split=0.2: The fraction of the training data to use for validation during training.

  1. The fit function returns a history object that contains information about the training process, such as loss and accuracy metrics for each epoch. We append this history object to the history_per_fold list for later analysis.

After training, we used the evaluate function to evaluate the model on the test data for the current fold. The evaluate function delivers the test data's loss and accuracy metrics. The accuracy score (multiplied by 100) and loss score are appended to the acc_per_fold and loss_per_fold lists, respectively.¶

For the following iteration of training and evaluation, we increment the fold number to go to the next fold.¶

Finally, we print the folds' scores and average metrics.¶

We may examine the model's performance and collect average scores to measure its generalization potential by repeating this process for each fold.¶

In [69]:
# Fit data to model
history = model.fit(inputs[train], targets[train], batch_size=256, epochs=10, validation_split=0.2)
history_per_fold.append(history)

# Generate generalization metrics
scores = model.evaluate(inputs[test], targets[test], verbose=0)
print(f'Score for fold {fold_no}: {model.metrics_names[0]} of {scores[0]}; {model.metrics_names[1]} of {scores[1]*100}%')
acc_per_fold.append(scores[1] * 100)
loss_per_fold.append(scores[0])

# Increase fold number
fold_no = fold_no + 1

# == Provide average scores ==
print('------------------------------------------------------------------------')
print('Score per fold')
for i in range(0, len(acc_per_fold)):
    print('------------------------------------------------------------------------')
    print(f'> Fold {i+1} - Loss: {loss_per_fold[i]} - Accuracy: {acc_per_fold[i]}%')

print('------------------------------------------------------------------------')
print('Average scores for all folds:')
print(f'> Accuracy: {np.mean(acc_per_fold)} (+- {np.std(acc_per_fold)})')
print(f'> Loss: {np.mean(loss_per_fold)}')
print('------------------------------------------------------------------------')

From these reslults we can conclude that:¶

  1. The model is performing moderately. There is very less variance among the accuracy scores of the 5 folds.

  1. Performing augmentation might enhance the performance of the model as the training set becomes more diverse on augmentation because of which the model performs better on unseen data.

  2. Also, increasing the number of epochs and batch size will also help improve the performance as having a bigger batch size means the model considers more data points while training through 1 epoch.

Overall, working with devices with better hardware specifications, we can perform these processes and improve the effieciency of our model.

In [70]:
for i, history in enumerate(history_per_fold, 1):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 4))
  
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'])
    plt.title('Model accuracy')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.legend(['Train', 'Test'], loc='upper left')

    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
    plt.title('Model loss')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.legend(['Train', 'Test'], loc='upper left')
    plt.show()

Overall, the accuracy of the model increases with each epoch and losses are coming down¶
